**`src/lib/supabase/authRepository.ts` â€” `buildAuthUser`**

Every login/session check does a tenant lookup, then (for owner/resident) a separate `user_unit_access` query. Called on every `getSession()` â€” i.e., every page load in Supabase mode.

```ts
// Current: 2 sequential round-trips per auth check
const { data: tenant } = await supabase.from('tenants').select('name').eq('id', tenantId).single();
// ...then a second await for user_unit_access
```

Fix: run independent queries concurrently, and consider a Postgres view/RPC that joins `user_profiles â†’ tenants â†’ user_unit_access â†’ units â†’ properties` in one call:

```ts
const [{ data: tenant }, { data: accessRows }] = await Promise.all([
  supabase.from('tenants').select('name').eq('id', tenantId).single(),
  (role === 'owner' || role === 'resident')
    ? supabase.from('user_unit_access').select('units(code, properties(code))').eq('user_id', profile.id as string)
    : Promise.resolve({ data: null })
]);
```

**`src/lib/supabase/dataRepository.ts` â€” mapper functions (`mapProperty`, `mapIssue`, etc.)**

These take `unitsData`/`issuesData` arrays and do `.filter()` inside a per-row mapper â€” that's O(nÂ·m) when called in a `.map()` loop over properties, effectively an in-memory N+1:

```ts
function mapProperty(row: any, unitsData: any[], issuesData: any[]): Property {
  const unitsCount = unitsData.filter((u) => u.property_id === row.id).length; // O(n) per property
  const issuesCount = issuesData.filter((i) => i.property_id === row.id && i.status !== 'Resolved').length;
  ...
}
```

Fix: pre-group once with `Map`, then O(1) lookups:

```ts
function groupBy<T>(rows: T[], key: (r: T) => string): Map<string, T[]> {
  const map = new Map<string, T[]>();
  for (const row of rows) {
    const k = key(row);
    if (!map.has(k)) map.set(k, []);
    map.get(k)!.push(row);
  }
  return map;
}

// build once before mapping all properties
const unitsByProperty = groupBy(unitsData, (u) => u.property_id);
const issuesByProperty = groupBy(issuesData, (i) => i.property_id);

function mapProperty(row: any, unitsByProperty: Map<string, any[]>, issuesByProperty: Map<string, any[]>): Property {
  const propUnits = unitsByProperty.get(row.id) ?? [];
  const unitsCount = propUnits.length;
  const issuesCount = (issuesByProperty.get(row.id) ?? []).filter((i) => i.status !== 'Resolved').length;
  ...
}
```
This matters more as property/unit counts grow â€” currently harmless at demo scale but scales quadratically.

**`src/lib/i18n.ts` â€” `useTranslation` hook**

Every component calling `useTranslation()` subscribes to a global `window` event and re-renders on any language change â€” fine in principle, but `t` is a new function on every render (not memoized), so any component passing `t` down as a prop, or using it inside a `useMemo`/`useCallback` dependency array, will invalidate memoization unnecessarily:

```ts
return {
  language,
  setLanguage,
  t: (key: TranslationKey) => translations[key][language] // new identity every render
};
```

Fix:
```ts
const t = useCallback((key: TranslationKey) => translations[key][language], [language]);
return useMemo(() => ({ language, setLanguage, t }), [language, t]);
```

**`src/components/AdminConsoleView.tsx` â€” `filteredUsers`**

This one is already correctly memoized with `useMemo` â€” good pattern, no issue. But note `canInviteRole` is recomputed every render (not expensive here, but if `canManageUserRole` grows costlier, wrap it in `useMemo([currentUser, inviteRole])`).

**`src/App.tsx` â€” large state tree with many `useState` slices**

App.tsx holds ~10+ independent `useState` slices (`properties`, `units`, `expenses`, `rules`, `issues`, `bankTransactions`, `paymentLedger`, `documents`, ...). Any single setter (e.g., `setIssues`) triggers a re-render of the entire `App` component tree, and since view components are likely receiving multiple of these arrays as props, most views re-render even when their own slice didn't change.

Fix options:
- Split state via `useReducer` for related domains, or
- Wrap heavy child views in `React.memo` with carefully selected props so unrelated state updates don't cascade:
```tsx
const MemoIssuesView = React.memo(IssuesView);
```
- Ensure derived arrays passed as props (e.g., `getVisibleIssues(...)`) are memoized with `useMemo`, not recomputed inline on every render â€” check call sites in the truncated `App.tsx`; if these scoping functions are called directly in JSX (not wrapped), they run on every render and produce new array references, breaking `React.memo` on children.

```tsx
// Likely current pattern (bad â€” new array reference every render, breaks memo children)
<IssuesView issues={getVisibleIssues(currentUser, issues, selectedProperty, properties)} />

// Fix
const visibleIssues = useMemo(
  () => getVisibleIssues(currentUser, issues, selectedProperty, properties),
  [currentUser, issues, selectedProperty, properties]
);
<IssuesView issues={visibleIssues} />
```

**`src/lib/propertyStatementAdapter.ts` â€” `buildStatements`, `toCalculationUnits`, `toCalculationExpenses`, `toCalculationRules`**

These pure transforms are likely called repeatedly (e.g., on every render of `StatementsView`, and again inside `calculateBalanceAfterPayment`) with the same `units`/`expenses`/`rules` inputs. Since they're pure functions of their inputs, they're perfect `useMemo` candidates at the call site:

```tsx
// In StatementsView or wherever buildStatements is called
const statements = useMemo(
  () => buildStatements({ period, units, expenses, rules }),
  [period, units, expenses, rules]
);
```

**`src/lib/paymentLedger.ts` â€” `calculateBalanceAfterPayment`**

Calls `buildStatements` (which itself does `generateStatements` over all units/expenses/rules) just to compute one unit's balance. If this runs per-row in a list (e.g., previewing balances for many units), it's redundant full recomputation each time:

```ts
export function calculateBalanceAfterPayment({ unitId, paymentAmount, period, units, expenses, rules }) {
  const statements = buildStatements({ period, units, expenses, rules }); // recomputes ALL units' statements
  ...
}
```

Fix: if called for multiple units, hoist `buildStatements` out and compute all balances from one shared statements result instead of recalculating per unit.

**`src/lib/supabase/authRepository.ts` â€” tenant name lookup**

`tenants.name` rarely changes; caching per `tenantId` in-memory (a simple `Map`) would eliminate a network round trip on every auth check:

```ts
const tenantNameCache = new Map<string, string>();

async function getTenantName(tenantId: string): Promise<string> {
  if (tenantNameCache.has(tenantId)) return tenantNameCache.get(tenantId)!;
  const { data } = await supabase.from('tenants').select('name').eq('id', tenantId).single();
  const name = data?.name ?? '';
  tenantNameCache.set(tenantId, name);
  return name;
}
```

**`src/lib/i18n.ts`** â€” event listener cleanup looks correct (`removeEventListener` in the `useEffect` cleanup), no leak here. Good pattern to keep.

**`src/App.tsx` â€” `supabaseInitialized` ref pattern**

Can't see the full effect body (file truncated), but this pattern commonly hides a leak: if there's an async `onAuthStateChange` subscription or interval tied to Supabase session watching, verify the cleanup function unsubscribes:

```ts
useEffect(() => {
  if (supabaseInitialized.current) return;
  supabaseInitialized.current = true;
  const { data: sub } = supabase.auth.onAuthStateChange((event, session) => { ... });
  return () => sub.subscription.unsubscribe(); // ensure this exists
}, []);
```
If this cleanup is missing, remounting `App` (e.g., in tests or HMR) accumulates duplicate auth listeners, each firing state updates on unmounted components.

**`localStorage`-backed state (`getSavedState`/`saveState`) in `App.tsx`**

Not a leak per se, but if there's a `useEffect` that calls `saveState` on every state change (common pattern for the ~10 state slices), each triggers a full `JSON.stringify` + `localStorage.setItem` synchronously on the main thread. At scale (large `units`/`expenses` arrays), this blocks rendering. Consider debouncing:

```ts
useEffect(() => {
  const id = setTimeout(() => saveState('hpm_issues', issues), 300);
  return () => clearTimeout(id);
}, [issues]);
```

**`src/lib/propertyStatementAdapter.ts` â€” `calculateCategoryShare` and `calculateSimulationRows`**

Both call `toCalculationUnits(units)` and `toCalculationRules(rules).find(...)` independently even when invoked back-to-back for multiple categories (e.g., in a simulation UI iterating categories). Each call re-maps the entire `units`/`rules` arrays:

```ts
// If called once per category in a loop, this redoes toCalculationUnits(units) every time
rules.forEach((rule) => calculateCategoryShare({ unit, category: rule.category, amount, units, rules }));
```

Fix: extract shared setup once for a batch:
```ts
export function calculateCategoryShares({ unit, categories, amounts, units, rules }: {...}) {
  const calculationUnits = toCalculationUnits(units); // computed once
  const calculationRules = toCalculationRules(rules); // computed once
  return categories.map((category) => {
    const rule = calculationRules.find((r) => r.categoryCode === category);
    if (!rule) return 0;
    const lines = calculateExpenseAllocation({ expense: { id: `preview-${category}`, categoryCode: category, amount: amounts[category] }, rule, units: calculationUnits });
    return lines.find((line) => line.unitCode === unit.id)?.amount || 0;
  });
}
```

**`src/lib/propertyStatementAdapter.ts` â€” `toCalculationUnits`**

Recomputes `getResidentsCount(unit)` (a hardcoded switch) on every call, but since it's a pure hardcoded lookup by `unit.id`, it's cheap â€” not a real bottleneck, but worth noting the hardcoded IDs (`'A1'`, `'A2'`, etc.) are a code smell more than a perf issue; this data should live on the `Unit` model itself (e.g., `residentsCount` field) rather than being recomputed via a switch every time statements are generated.

**`src/lib/vat.ts` â€” `isValidGreekVat`**

Calls `vatDigits(input)` which calls `normalizeVat(input)` â€” fine as-is (cheap), no action needed. Mentioned only to confirm it was checked; no redundant work found here.

